#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:90
msgid "The authentication process"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:92
msgid "How Cargo will generate an asymmetric token"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:94
msgid ""
"When authenticating to a registry, Cargo will generate a PASETO in the [v3."
"public format](https://github.com/paseto-standard/paseto-spec/blob/master/"
"docs/01-Protocol-Versions/Version3.md). This format uses P-384 and 384-bit "
"ECDSA secret keys, and is compatible with keys stored in contemporary "
"hardware tokens. The generated PASETO will have specific \"claims\" (key-"
"value pairs in the PASETO's JSON payload)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:96
msgid ""
"All PASETOs will include `iat`, the current time in ISO 8601 format. Cargo "
"will include the following where appropriate:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:97
msgid ""
"`sub` an optional, non-secret string chosen by the registry that is expected "
"to be claimed with every request. The value will be the `private-key-"
"subject` from the `config.toml` file."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:98
msgid ""
"`mutation` if present, indicates that this request is a mutating operation "
"(or a read-only operation if not present), must be one of the strings "
"`publish`, `yank`, or `unyank`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:99
msgid "`name` name of the crate related to this request."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:100
msgid "`vers` version string of the crate related to this request."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:101
msgid ""
"`cksum` the SHA256 hash of the crate contents, as a string of 64 lowercase "
"hexadecimal digits, must be present only when `mutation` is equal to "
"`publish`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:102
msgid ""
"`challenge` the challenge string received from a 401/403 from this server "
"this session. Registries that issue challenges must track which challenges "
"have been issued/used and never accept a given challenge more than once "
"within the same validity period (avoiding the need to track every challenge "
"ever issued)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:104
msgid ""
"The \"footer\" (which is part of the signature) will be a JSON string in "
"UTF-8 and include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:105
msgid "`url` the RFC 3986 compliant URL where cargo got the config.json file,"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:106
msgid ""
"If this is a registry with an HTTP index, then this is the base URL that all "
"index queries are relative to."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:107
msgid ""
"If this is a registry with a GIT index, it is the URL Cargo used to clone "
"the index."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:108
msgid ""
"`kid` the identifier of the private key used to sign the request, using the "
"[PASERK IDs](https://github.com/paseto-standard/paserk/blob/master/"
"operations/ID.md) standard."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:110
msgid ""
"PASETO includes the message that was signed, so the server does not have to "
"reconstruct the exact string from the request in order to check the "
"signature. The server does need to check that the signature is valid for the "
"string in the PASETO and that the contents of that string matches the "
"request. If a claim should be expected for the request but is missing in the "
"PASETO then the request must be rejected."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:113
msgid "How the Registry Server will validate an asymmetric token"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:115
msgid ""
"The registry server will validate the PASETO, and check the footer and "
"claims:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:117
msgid "The PASETO is in v3.public format."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:118
msgid ""
"The PASETO validates using the public key it looked up based on the `key ID`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:119
msgid ""
"The URL matches the registry base URL (to make sure a PASETO sent to one "
"registry can't be used to authenticate to another, and to prevent "
"typosquatting/homoglyph attacks)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:120
msgid ""
"The PASETO is still within its valid time period (to limit replay attacks). "
"We recommend a 15 minute limit, but a shorter time can be used by a registry "
"to further decrease replayability. Or a longer one can be used to better "
"accommodate clock skew."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:121
msgid ""
"If the claim `v` is set, that it has the value of `1`. (This future proofs "
"against breaking changes in newer RFCs.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:122
msgid ""
"If the server issues challenges, that the challenge has not yet been "
"answered. Registries that issue challenges must track which challenges have "
"been issued/used and never accept a given challenge more than once within "
"the same validity period (avoiding the need to track every challenge ever "
"issued)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:123
msgid "If the operation is a mutation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:124
msgid ""
"That the operation matches the `mutation` field an is one of `publish`, "
"`yank`, or `unyank`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:125
msgid "That the package, and version match the request."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:126
msgid ""
"If the mutation is `publish`, that the version has not already been "
"published, and that the hash matches the request."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:127
msgid "If the operation is a read, that the `mutation` field is not set."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:129
msgid ""
"See the [Appendix: Token Examples](#token-examples) for a walk through of "
"constructing some tokens."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:131
msgid ""
"We recommend the use of challenges to prevent some replay attacks. For "
"example, if I accidentally `unyank` a version and then realize my mistake "
"and `yank` that version again, an attacker with a copy of the traffic could "
"replay the `unyank` request, reverting my `yank`. This replay attack should "
"be prevented by using single-use challenges that registries must invalidate "
"when they are used."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:133
msgid "Credential Processes"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:135
msgid ""
"Credential Processes as defined in [RFC 2730](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rfcs/pull/2730) are outside programs cargo can call on to change where and "
"how secrets are stored. That RFC defines `special strings` which go in the "
"`credential-process` field to describe what data the process needs from "
"cargo. This RFC adds `{claims}`. If used Cargo will replace it with a JSON "
"encoded set of key value pairs that should be in the generated token. Cargo "
"will check that the output of such a process looks like a valid PASETO v3."
"public token that Cargo would have generated, and that the PASETO token "
"includes all the claims Cargo provided. The credential process may add "
"additional claims (e.g. 2fa, TOTP), as long as they are nested in `custom`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:137
msgid ""
"Some credential processes that might be useful for people to develop include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:138
msgid ""
"The ability to store keys in operating systems specific secure enclaves."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:139
msgid "the ability to use keys embedded in common hardware tokens."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:140
msgid ""
"The ability to read keys in formats used by other tools (GPG, SSH, PKCS#12, "
"etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:142
msgid "Note on stability"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:144
msgid ""
"This is just a reminder to check if there are newer RFCs that have had to "
"deprecate, remove, or replace parts of this one. RFCs can always be adjusted "
"by new RFCs. In general the Rust community takes backwards compatibility "
"very seriously, so if an RFC says you can do something no future RFC is "
"likely to say that you cannot do that thing. It has happened, RFCs have been "
"amended or changed by subsequent RFCs. The content of this RFC is full of "
"details with security implications. It is not unlikely that in the course of "
"human events changes will need to be made to it. Hopefully, they can be made "
"by loosening restrictions or supporting new formats. But, because security "
"is involved the Rust community may be more likely to break backward "
"compatibility than is our norm."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:146
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:149
msgid ""
"This gets Cargo involved in the cryptographic standards used by registries, "
"which puts a lot of complexity on ourselves. Now rust teams need to be "
"involved in conversations about what cryptographic standards alternative "
"registries choose to use."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:151
msgid ""
"Furthermore, this RFC attempts to make a start on solving several problems "
"at the same time. It may be that in time we discover these problems need to "
"be solved separately. If we end up with a separate system for code signing "
"and a separate system for authorization, then a simpler more direct method "
"of authentication might have been a better choice."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:153
msgid "Rationale and alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:156
msgid ""
"Continue with the existing secret tokens. Private registries that want to "
"provide this kind of functionality can create a bespoke system for their "
"exact needs. For example, only generating short-lived tokens and having the "
"user log in daily. In practice, I suspect many registries will not, leading "
"to an ecosystem where most registries use less secure authentication, and "
"creating more hazards for users. Some security properties (e.g. not "
"supporting tokens from one registry on another) work better when all "
"registries support them."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:159
msgid ""
"We could use PASETO `v4.public` instead of `v3.public`. The `v4` standard "
"uses more modern crypto, based on Ed25519. Unfortunately, most existing "
"hardware tokens do not support Ed25519. By using `v3.public` based on P-384 "
"we allow a `credential-process` to keep keys on the hardware."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:162
msgid ""
"We could use [Amazon's SigV4](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/general/latest/gr/"
"signature-version-4.html). In SigV4 the client constructs a string from the "
"request (url, headers, and body). The client signs the string. It sends the "
"signature and only the signature as the authentication with the request. "
"Importantly the client does not send the constructed string. The server "
"looks at the request it receives and construct a new copy of the string. It "
"then checks that the signature it got is valid for the string it "
"constructed. This scheme means that the authentication field stays the same "
"size no matter how much is being signed. Also, any large data sent in the "
"request is not duplicated in the authentication header. Most importantly "
"there is no way for a server to have a bug where it forgets to check that "
"some fields in the token do not match the request it came with! "
"Unfortunately this scheme is more complicated than it seems. There is a lot "
"of complexity hidden in \"constructs a string\". SigV4 does not get us out "
"of  having to specify exactly which fields are important for each request. "
"Furthermore, HTTP headers and urls can be canonicalised differently by "
"different hops on the network. when calling Amazon's services Amazon "
"provides client libraries that do all the heavy lifting of making sure the "
"fields are canonicalised the same on the client and the server if and only "
"if the requests are for the same resource. A lot of this complexity's has "
"been standardized and generalized in the [HTTP Message Signatures](https://"
"www.ietf.org/archive/id/draft-ietf-httpbis-message-signatures-08.html) draft "
"specification. Unfortunately, implementations of the specification are not "
"yet widely available."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:165
msgid ""
"Mutating operations include signed proof that the asymmetric token was "
"intended for that package, version, and hash. Why not do the same for read "
"operations? When reading from an HTTP based index, we may need to request "
"many files in quick succession without being able to enumerate them in "
"advance. When using a credential process to communicate with a hardware "
"token that requires human interaction for each signing operation we do not "
"want to require hundreds of interactions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:167
msgid ""
"Use [Biscuit](https://www.biscuitsec.org/) instead of PASETO. Biscuit is a "
"format that adds delegation and a logic-based policy engine for attenuation "
"and fine-grained usage controls to the other properties tokens have. The "
"Biscuit logic language provides a centralized place to do authorization. As "
"part of the token format, for example, a token can be made that can only "
"publish one crate on a particular day (good for a CI/CD use case), or a "
"token that can only yank particular crates (good for giving to a security "
"scanner). Once biscuit is adopted as your token format [the crates.io token "
"scopes RFC](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/2947) becomes easy to "
"implement. Authorization with tokens that have limited scope are definitely "
"something more widely used registries should definitely support. If we use "
"Biscuit all the controls anyone could ask for are just part of the system."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:170
msgid "However:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:171
msgid ""
"Introducing it here for authentication means that all registries need to use "
"the biscuit language for their authorization. For some small registries this "
"will be a lot more controls than they need. For large registries they will "
"need to build compatibility between whatever existing authorization system "
"they have and their biscuit implementation."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:172
msgid ""
"The biscuit language has some pretty complicated primitives, including "
"regular expressions. Registries that require thorough correctness audits for "
"all code related to Auth may find this prohibitively expensive."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:173
msgid ""
"The current biscuit specification (2.0) does not have a rich model of "
"authentication. If you have a token that was authorized to do the action you "
"are attempting to do then you must be someone who is allowed to do that "
"action. Which has a lot of the same limitations of the existing secret token "
"system as outlined in the motivation section of this RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:174
msgid ""
"It is still possible to do scopes for tokens without using biscuits. A user "
"ID can be created for each authorized role, and then the server can make "
"sure that the used user ID is authorized to do the intended action."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:176
msgid "Prior art"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:179
msgid ""
"NuGet has support for [author signing](https://github.com/NuGet/Home/wiki/"
"Author-Package-Signing), which can be used to make sure that publishes only "
"happen from somebody who has a private key. This system allows authenticity "
"to be checked looking only at the crate that is downloaded. However, in "
"order to participate the author must have a \"code signing certificate\" "
"from a \"trusted root authority\", making the barrier to participation to "
"high for most users and certainly too high to be considered a norm of the "
"community."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:182
msgid ""
"Maven Central [requires](https://maven.apache.org/repository/guide-central-"
"repository-upload.html#pgp-signature) all uploads to be [signed by PGP]"
"(https://central.sonatype.org/publish/requirements/gpg/) and that the keys "
"are registered with a public key server. Following the UNIX philosophy, they "
"leave the actual act of signing up to independent implementations of PGP. It "
"takes a lot of documentation to explain how to hook up all of these "
"different parts to work together correctly. Furthermore, no assurance is "
"made that the GPG signature and the Maven Central token used for upload "
"represent the same identity."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:185
msgid ""
"The npm client can pass along a `otp` option on the command line to act as "
"[proof of 2FA](https://docs.npmjs.com/configuring-two-factor-"
"authentication#sending-a-one-time-password-from-the-command-line). This "
"provides a lot of the \"over the wire\" benefits of this RFC for the npm "
"registry, but cannot be used by a third party after the fact to verify the "
"uploaded identity."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:187
msgid ""
"[TUF](https://theupdateframework.io/) exclusively deals with how a client "
"downloading packages through a mirror can be assured they came from a non-"
"compromised copy of the registry. Which is not the problem this RFC is "
"addressing."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:189
msgid "Unresolved questions"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:192
msgid ""
"How aggressively to push people off secret tokens? This RFC does not remove "
"the existing use of secret tokens for publishing and yanking on private "
"registries nor suggests a timeline for crates.io to use asymmetric tokens. "
"There is an [RFC to allow authentication on more operations](https://github."
"com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/f3aecb96eeb95542d81d6dc6b0a22c1245383604/text/0000-"
"cargo-alternative-registry-auth.md), the expectation is that we will require "
"the use of asymmetric tokens for this new functionality. This is a question "
"that we will have to decide as we go through implementation and "
"stabilization."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:194
msgid ""
"What default settings should `cargo login --generate-keypair` use? What "
"process should be used for changing these defaults as best practice changes? "
"Where should it put the private keys?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:196
msgid ""
"More generally, is all the user experience exactly correct for all the new "
"CLI flags? The expectation is that these will need to be changed and tweaked "
"as we try using them after implementation."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:198
msgid "Future possibilities"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:201
msgid ""
"Figuring out how and when crates.io should support these kinds of tokens is "
"left to a follow-up discussion/RFC. The motivation section describes some of "
"the things that will need to be figured out."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:203
msgid ""
"Only after crates.io is not using secret tokens should we consider removing "
"the support for them in private registries (and the code in cargo to support "
"it)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:205
msgid ""
"After that an audit log of what tokens were used to publish on crates.io and "
"why that token was trusted, would probably be a rich data source for "
"identifying compromised accounts. As well as making it possible to do end to "
"end signature verification. The crate file I downloaded matches the `cksum` "
"in the index; the index matches the `cksum` in the audit log; the public key "
"used in the audit log is the one I expected."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:207
msgid ""
"This scheme could be augmented to allow the use of several signing "
"technologies. We would need to add a way for a registry to express what "
"formats it will accept. We would need to add code for cargo to check that "
"the credential provider was following one of the accepted formats. We would "
"need to add code for cargo to generate the additional formats. But none of "
"this is out of the question, so there is a clear path forward when algorithm "
"agility is required."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:209
msgid "Appendix"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:211
msgid "Threat Model"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:213
msgid ""
"If a registry were set up to exclusively use the new asymmetric tokens, how "
"well would it handle the issues in the motivation?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:217
msgid ""
"`credentials.toml` name identifies that it should not be shared. "
"Unfortunately, this RFC does not make things better."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:221
msgid ""
"Many more kinds of security hardware devices can protect a private key then "
"can protect an arbitrary secret token. Hardware devices can store a private "
"key and only perform operations using that key, without making the key "
"itself available."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:225
msgid ""
"It is still possible for someone to log the private key. However, the signed "
"asymmetric token is not secret. So all other things (like network traffic) "
"can be logged safely."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:229
msgid ""
"Content shared over the network is not secret. The opportunity for replay "
"attacks is significantly limited. If the operation is mutating then the "
"token can only be used for the intended operation. If it is a read "
"operation, if the request returns meaningful results then the attacker can "
"already see it without reusing the token. But, as the token includes the URL "
"it can not be used on the `https` address."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:233
msgid ""
"The asymmetric token includes the URL so the signature is only valid for "
"that URL, the token is not valid for the real registry."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:237
msgid ""
"There is no reason for the registry to even see the private key. Even if the "
"registry wants to generate keys for its users there is no need to store "
"private keys. Disclosure of public keys is not a security risk, as they can "
"not be used to sign new asymmetric tokens."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:239
msgid ""
"To be fair, there's no reason for a registry based on secret tokens to store "
"them in a recoverable format. The registry can store secret token hashes "
"instead, and avoid this problem without inconveniencing the user. Since "
"secret tokens are already random, you can avoid a lot of the complexities of "
"storing passwords."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:241
msgid ""
"Storing plain text secret tokens is only a problem in practice not in "
"theory. However, the link is to an example of crates.io getting this wrong. "
"I can only assume if we have seen one registry get this wrong, then there "
"are others and there will be more in the future."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:243
msgid ""
"Fundamentally these are all problems only because once an attacker has seen "
"a secret token they have all that is needed to act on that user's behalf."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:245
msgid ""
"Without the private key an asymmetric token can only be used for the "
"intended registry, for the intended action, and for a limited amount of "
"time. This mitigates the risk of disclosure."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:247
msgid "Token Examples"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:249
msgid "A Simple Read Operation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:251
msgid ""
"For example: If cargo needs to construct an asymmetric token for a simple "
"read operation it will gather some basic information:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:252
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:287
msgid ""
"The private key ([`PASERK` secret format](https://github.com/paseto-standard/"
"paserk/blob/master/types/secret.md)): `\"k3.secret."
"fNYVuMvBgOlljt9TDohnaYLblghqaHoQquVZwgR6X12cBFHZLFsaU3q7X3k1Zn36\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:253
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:289
msgid "The current time: `\"2022-02-28T18:33:24+00:00\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:254
msgid ""
"The url to the root of the index: `\"https://registry.com/crate-index\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:256
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:298
msgid "It will then derive:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:257
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:299
msgid ""
"The public key for the private key ([`PASERK` public format](https://github."
"com/paseto-standard/paserk/blob/master/types/public.md)): `\"k3.public."
"AmDwjlyf8jAV3gm5Z7Kz9xAOcsKslt_Vwp5v-emjFzBHLCtcANzTaVEghTNEMj9PkQ\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:258
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:300
msgid ""
"The [`PASERK ID`](https://github.com/paseto-standard/paserk/blob/master/"
"operations/ID.md) for the public key: `\"k3.pid."
"QB3WNBP-5j-0XQV2MOuvuOcLlJ8uz-pmqtIZus1x3YTu\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:260
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:302
msgid ""
"It will then construct a PASETO in the [v3.public format](https://github.com/"
"paseto-standard/paseto-spec/blob/master/docs/01-Protocol-Versions/Version3."
"md). In this case:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:265
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:307
msgid ""
"The server will validate that this looks like a properly formatted `v3."
"public` PASETO. It will decode the footer and get:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:267
msgid ""
"```\n"
"{\"url\": \"https://registry.com/crate-index\", \"kid\": \"k3.pid."
"QB3WNBP-5j-0XQV2MOuvuOcLlJ8uz-pmqtIZus1x3YTu\"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:270
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:312
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:320
msgid "It will check that:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:271
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:313
msgid "The `url` is for the index of the registry that the request is for."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:272
msgid "The `kid` is for a public key it has on file."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:273
msgid ""
"The PASETO signature can be validated using the public key related to `kid`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:275
#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:315
msgid "It can then decode the payload and get:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:276
msgid ""
"```\n"
"{\"iat\": \"2022-02-28T18:33:24+00:00\"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:279
msgid ""
"It will check that the `iat` is within the valid time period picked by the "
"server. Given that there is no mutation claim, it will check that the "
"request is a read. (A read token can be used for multiple requests. See "
"[Rationale and alternatives](#rationale-and-alternatives) for why.) At this "
"point the server has validated the PASETO, it should now go on to "
"determining if the user associated with this public key should be allowed to "
"read this object."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:284
msgid "A Complicated Publish Operation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:286
msgid ""
"For example: If cargo needs to construct an asymmetric token for a "
"complicated publish operation it will gather some basic information:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:288
msgid "The `private-key-subject` for that key: `\"private-key-subject\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:290
msgid ""
"The url to the root of the index: `\"https://registry-challenge-subject.com/"
"crate-index\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:291
msgid "The challenge received from the most recent 401/403: `\"challenge\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:293
msgid "Because it's a published operation cargo will also gather:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:294
msgid "The crate name: `\"foo\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:295
msgid "The crate version: `\"0.0.0\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:296
msgid ""
"The hash of the `.crate` file: "
"`\"f7dbb6acfeff1d490fba693a402456f76b344fea77a5e7cae43b5970c3332b8f\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:309
msgid ""
"```\n"
"{\"url\": \"https://registry-challenge-subject.com/crate-index\", \"kid\": "
"\"k3.pid.QB3WNBP-5j-0XQV2MOuvuOcLlJ8uz-pmqtIZus1x3YTu\"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:316
msgid ""
"```\n"
"{\"challenge\": \"challenge\", \"mutation\": \"publish\", \"name\": \"foo\", "
"\"vers\": \"0.0.0\", \"cksum\": "
"\"f7dbb6acfeff1d490fba693a402456f76b344fea77a5e7cae43b5970c3332b8f\", "
"\"sub\": \"private-key-subject\", \"iat\": \"2022-02-28T18:33:24+00:00\"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:321
msgid "The `iat` is within the valid time period picked by the server."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:322
msgid "The `sub` and `kid` is for a public key it has on file."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:323
msgid "The PASETO signature can be validated using that public key."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:324
msgid "The `challenge` was issued by this server and has not been revoked."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:326
msgid "Given that there is a mutation claim it will check that:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:327
msgid "The request is for a `publish`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:328
msgid "The request is to publish a crate with the same name as `name`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:329
msgid "The request is to publish a crate with the same version as `vers`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:330
msgid "The request is to publish a crate with the same hash as `cksum`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3231-cargo-asymmetric-tokens.md:332
msgid ""
"At this point the server has validated the PASETO, it should now go on to "
"determining if the user associated with this public key should be allowed to "
"publish this object."
msgstr ""
